comment.narrative:
During project's lifetime:
1) All 17,000 properties have been registered;
2) Through support to the environmental agencies, 50% of the total area of all registered properties have been analyzed and validated; 
3) Through support for farmers, 25% of all the properties (0,25% *3,400 = 850 properties, see assumption) with a deficit in Permanent Protection Areas or Legal Reserves have been supported with the preparation of a proposal on how to restore or offset their deficit;
4) 50% of farms analyzed and validated. 34,000 farmers and their family members (17,000 men and 17,000 women) are directly beneficiaries in having their properties regularized;
5) Deforestation reduction to rates around 6000km2 in the Matopiba region;
6) Deforestation reduction by 1000km2 over three years in the Matopiba region. Better monitoring and control and the implementation of the Forest Code is expected to reduce the annual deforestation rate by 1000 km2 at the end of the project.

1) 23,258,00 properties have been registered (by June 28th, 2019) in SICAR. This already exceeds the end-of-project target;
2 and 3) 414.358,49 ha analyzed of the 5.056.690,31 ha registered = 8.2% as of April 2019. *The status of a registered farm can be changed from ‘analyzed’ to ‘under analysis’ if any inconsistencies are detected by the Brazilian Forestry Service with respect to unauthorized reallocation of the Permanent Protected Areas or Legal Reserves or changes in the total size of the property. In this case, the registry will need to go through the analysis process again and its area is no longer added to the total area registered in the municipality.	3) The support for the analysis of the registered properties already started with the signature of the Cooperation Agreements with both state environmental agencies in Tocantins and Bahia. In early April, a workshop was held with technical experts from these agencies to discuss the CAR validation processes, mainly challenges and gaps perceived concerning the existing governmental structure. Through the exchange of experiences, we identified priorities in each of the states to be properly addressed within the work plan developed under the Cooperation Agreements;
4)The Brazilian government concluded the update of its agricultural census in the second semester of 2018 and these data are now publicly available. Information was downloaded by CI’s team and is currently going through the filtering process to be incorporated as an indicator of the beneficiaries of the project. The preliminary results will be available in March/April 2020. 
5 and 6) As part of the work undertaken within component 3 we were able to significantly improve data quality. This effort will impact the reduction rate, since the baseline was not calculated using accurate data. We are updating the spatial database and carrying out a detailed analysis to be able to report accurately. In 2018, according to data provided by the Brazilian Ministry of Environment (MMA), around 6,657 km² of native vegetation in the Cerrado were lost. External factors are influencing the increase of national deforestation rates in general, mainly the domestic political context, with the election of Jair Bolsonaro and the ongoing debate on the Forest Code flexibilization that may accelerate both legal (and illegal) deforestation.

During project's lifetime:
1) All 17,000 properties have been registered;
2) Through support to the environmental agencies, 50% of the total area of all registered properties have been analyzed and validated; 
3) Through support for farmers, 25% of all the properties (0,25% *3,400 = 850 properties, see assumption) with a deficit in Permanent Protection Areas or Legal Reserves have been supported with the preparation of a proposal on how to restore or offset their deficit;
4) 50% of farms analyzed and validated. 34,000 farmers and their family members (17,000 men and 17,000 women) are directly beneficiaries in having their properties regularized;
5) Deforestation reduction to rates around 6000km2 in the Matopiba region;
6) Deforestation reduction by 1000km2 over three years in the Matopiba region. Better monitoring and control and the implementation of the Forest Code is expected to reduce the annual deforestation rate by 1000 km2 at the end of the project.

According to 2018 PIR:
1) 20,602 properties have been registered  (up to June 18th, 2018) in SICAR. This already exceeds the end-of-project target;
2) 657,340.95 ha analyzed of the 4,599,610.31 ha registered = 14% as of March 2018. *The status of a registered farm can be changed from ‘analyzed’ to ‘under analysis’ if any inconsistencies are detected by the Brazilian Forestry Service with respect to unauthorized reallocation of the Permanent Protected Areas or Legal Reserves or changes in the total size of the property. In this case, the registry will need to go through the analysis process again and its area is no longer added to the total area registered in the municipality;
3) The support for the analysis of the registered properties will start in the coming months, after signature of the Cooperation Agreements with both state environmental agencies in Tocantins and Bahia. In Tocantins the agreement has been signed and we are about to hire technical support. In Bahia we are in the final steps to get state government approval;
4) The Brazilian government is in the process of concluding the update of its agricultural census in the second semester of 2018. Once these official data become publicly available, CI will verify the number of beneficiaries per family (men and women) based on the number of properties analyzed and validated. In addition, we are negotiating an agreement with AIBA (Association of Irrigants and Agriculturists of Bahia) to work closely with the associated producers. With the agreement signed we will have much more precise data on direct beneficiaries;
5 and 6) In the last 2 years (2016-2017), deforestation has actually increased. However, it is important to highlight that the increase is not directly related to project interventions. As part of the work undertaken within component 3 we were able to significantly improve data quality. This effort will impact the reduction rate, since the baseline was not calculated using accurate data. We are updating the spatial database and carrying out a detailed analysis to be able to report accurately. Nevertheless, we also believe other external factors are influencing the increase registered. External factors here include the debate on the forest code and the extension of the CAR deadline, which may have  generated a rebound effect. Until the window is closed, landowners may accelerate legal deforestation, taking advantage of the political window of opportunity created. This can impact increasing deforestation in the region.
